Also known as blood poisoning.  Septicaemia is caused by the presence of toxin-producing bacteria in the blood stream.  Characteristic symptoms include fever, rigors, mental confusion, tachycardia and hypotension in the early stages.  This can progress to serious conditions such as septic shock, disseminated intrvascular coagulation (DIC) and acute renal failure.

Diagnosis is made by examining blood cultures and treatment by way of antibiotics.